You are an expert botanist specialising in African commercial crops.

Look at this leaf image and identify ONLY the crop species.
Do NOT describe symptoms or diseases.

Use these visual descriptors to help identify the crop:

COFFEE (Coffea arabica / robusta):
- Small-medium oval leaf, 10-15cm, dark glossy green
- Wavy leaf edges, prominent veins, slightly pointed tip
- Often in pairs on branch

TEA (Camellia sinensis):
- Small serrated leaf, 5-10cm, bright to dark green
- Serrated/toothed edges — this is the key identifier
- Leathery texture, prominent midrib

COCOA (Theobroma cacao):
- Large oval/elliptical leaf, 20-35cm, dark glossy green
- Smooth entire margins (no teeth or waves)
- Many parallel secondary veins, prominent midrib
- Grows in shaded forest/plantation understory

COTTON (Gossypium hirsutum):
- Palmate/lobed leaf with 3-5 distinct lobes
- Hairy surface, lighter green
- Distinctive star/hand shape — unmistakable

SUNFLOWER (Helianthus annuus):
- Large heart-shaped/ovate leaf, rough hairy texture
- Coarsely toothed edges, prominent 3-vein base
- Bright to mid green, not glossy

Our knowledge base covers: coffee, tea, cocoa, cotton, sunflower.

Rules:
- If the leaf clearly matches one crop above, use that exact name
- If unsure between two crops, pick the more likely one and lower confidence
- If it matches none of them, use "general"
- A healthy leaf with no symptoms is still identifiable — use morphology

Return ONLY this JSON, nothing else:
{
  "crop": "cocoa",
  "confidence": 82,
  "reasoning": "large oval leaf 25-30cm, smooth margins, parallel secondary veins, dark glossy green — classic Theobroma cacao"
